Looking at the `PersistenceController`, I can see that the CloudKit fix is in place:

```swift
// CloudKit sync only for on-disk stores — never for in-memory preview/test stores.
// In-memory stores can't use CloudKit (no real store file for metadata),
// and Swift Testing runs suites in parallel so multiple test instances would
// race over CloudKit metadata tables and deadlock.
if !inMemory {
    description.setOption(true as NSNumber, forKey: NSPersistentHistoryTrackingKey)
    description.setOption(true as NSNumber, forKey: NSPersistentStoreRemoteChangeNotificationPostOptionKey)
    description.cloudKitContainerOptions = NSPersistentCloudKitContainerOptions(
        containerIdentifier: "iCloud.ink.kerry.souvenir"
    )
}
```

So CloudKit options are only configured when using an on-disk store, but the real question is whether `NSPersistentCloudKitContainer` itself initiates CloudKit operations even without those options being set.

According to Apple's documentation, `NSPersistentCloudKitContainer` only attempts to sync when `cloudKitContainerOptions` is explicitly configured on the store description. Without it, the container behaves like a standard `NSPersistentContainer` and shouldn't make any CloudKit network calls. That should prevent the spinning issue the user mentioned, but I should run the tests to confirm this is actually resolved now.

